From: r1mx <r1mx@r1mx>
Subject: [PATCH 2/3] target/ppc: truncate vaddr to target_ulong in ppc_cpu_tlb_fill

For 32-bit PPC, ppc_cpu_tlb_fill receives eaddr as vaddr (uint64_t).
TARGET_PAGE_MASK is (int32_t)(-4096) which sign-extends to 64 bits in
mixed-type arithmetic:

    0x100000000 & 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFF000 == 0x100000000  (WRONG for PPC32)

The value 0x100000000 arises when the PPC32 program counter wraps:
0xFFFFFFFC + 4 = 0x100000000 in 64-bit arithmetic, even though the
CPU register truncates to 0x00000000.  Without the cast, the TLB entry
for page 0 receives xlat_section = iotlb - 0x100000000 = a large negative
value, causing a SIGSEGV in notdirty_write when the dirty-page bitmap is
accessed at a bogus host address.

Fix: cast eaddr to target_ulong (uint32_t for PPC32) before masking so
0x100000000 becomes 0x00000000 and the TLB entry for page 0 is correct.

--- a/target/ppc/mmu_helper.c
+++ b/target/ppc/mmu_helper.c
@@ -1381,8 +1381,15 @@ bool ppc_cpu_tlb_fill(CPUState *cs, vaddr eaddr, int size,
     if (ppc_xlate(cpu, eaddr, access_type, &raddr,
                   &page_size, &prot, mmu_idx, !probe)) {
-        tlb_set_page(cs, eaddr & TARGET_PAGE_MASK, raddr & TARGET_PAGE_MASK,
-                     prot, mmu_idx, 1UL << page_size);
+        /*
+         * For 32-bit PPC, eaddr is a vaddr (uint64_t) but must be
+         * truncated to target_ulong (uint32_t) before masking.  Without
+         * the cast, TARGET_PAGE_MASK sign-extends from int32_t to 64-bit
+         * so 0x100000000 & mask = 0x100000000 instead of 0x00000000.
+         */
+        tlb_set_page(cs, (target_ulong)eaddr & TARGET_PAGE_MASK,
+                     raddr & TARGET_PAGE_MASK,
+                     prot, mmu_idx, 1UL << page_size);
         return true;
     }
